strict, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Berrynarbor, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Narbert","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German, Dutch, and French: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Nordberht</i>, composed of the elements <i>nord</i> ‘north’ and <i>berht</i> ‘bright’."],"variants":[{"name":"Nobert","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Normand, Gaston, Henri, Huguette, Marcel.","French (Alsace and Lorraine) and German: variant of   Norbert  . This surname is very rare in both France and Germany."]},{"name":"Norberto","meanings":["Portuguese and Spanish: from the personal name <i>Norberto</i>, of ancient Germanic origin (see   Norbert  )."]},{"name":"Nord","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Erik, Helmer, Alvar, Knute, Nels, Per.","Swedish and Danish: ornamental (Swedish) or topographic (Danish) name from <i>nord</i> ‘north’. As a topographic name it would have denoted someone who lived in the northern part of a village or to the north of a main settlement or someone who had migrated from the north.","Norwegian: habitational name from the farm name Nor in Fjordane in western Norway (from <i>nór</i> ‘narrow waters, strait’), or from the farm name Nord ‘north’, denoting a farm lying to the north of another farm."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Wevers","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French: habitational name from the city of Nevers in France.","Possibly an altered form of English   Nevard   or perhaps of its extinct variant <b>Neverd</b>. The surname <i>Nevers</i> is also found in Jamaica.","History: The majority of the American bearers of this surname trace their origin to Richard Nevers, born in 1666 in Woburn, MA. His origin is not known, but his surname is also documented in the forms <i>Nevard</i> and <i>Neverds</i>, which make it possible that Richard Nevers was of English origin."],"variants":[{"name":"Nevard","meanings":["(2010: NA)","English: from the Middle English (Old French) personal name <i>Nevard</i>, from ancient Germanic <i>Niwhard</i>, from <i>niw-</i> ‘new’ + <i>hard-</i> ‘strong, hardy’. Compare   Nevers  ."]}]},{"name":"Clarissa","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Clarice   occasionally found in medieval documents. It was revived by  Samuel Richardson  as the name of the central character in his novel Clarissa (  1748 ) and has since remained in moderate use."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Clarissa Narbert de Wevers was born in 1247, in Devon, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of Willmus Narbert de Wevers De Berry. She had at least 1 son with William De Berry. She died in Berrynarbor, Devon, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1247–":"1247–Surnud","1247–Female":"1247–Surnud","1247–Male":"1247–Surnud","1282–Male":"1282–Surnud","1220–Male":"1220–Surnud","about 1282":"umbes 1282","1247":"1247","1220":"1220","1282":"1282","Berrynarbor, Devon, England":"Berrynarbor, Devon, England","Berrynarbor, North Devon district, Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"